The direction of electric current is defined as the direction in which positive charges would move. Most commonly, a circuit contains a power source, conductors, and a load.
The circuit can be a closed loop, a closed network, or an open loop. In a closed network, the current flows around the circuit. In an open circuit, the current cannot flow. In a series circuit, the current flows through each component in turn. In a parallel circuit, the current flows through each component in parallel.
In electrical engineering, the term circuit is also used for the electrical network that a power source provides. This is sometimes called a power circuit.

Resistors are made of a material with a high resistivity, such as carbon, brick oxide, metal oxide, or metal.
